1
00:01:33,607 --> 00:01:36,405
...who took care
of those around him.

2
00:01:36,443 --> 00:01:40,243
And l know that
in this time of sadness,

3
00:01:40,280 --> 00:01:44,478
he would have been glad,
to know of the support

4
00:01:44,518 --> 00:01:46,486
that his friends
have provided.

5
00:01:46,520 --> 00:01:49,284
Those who are here...

6
00:01:49,322 --> 00:01:51,290
A friend of yours?

7
00:01:51,324 --> 00:01:54,623
A customer.
Well, ex-customer.

8
00:01:54,661 --> 00:01:57,027
Oh.

9
00:01:57,063 --> 00:01:59,031
How old was he?

10
00:01:59,065 --> 00:02:01,033
43.

11
00:02:01,067 --> 00:02:04,195
43? That's young.

12
00:02:04,237 --> 00:02:06,205
What did he die of?

13
00:02:06,239 --> 00:02:09,231
Blue ice.

14
00:02:09,276 --> 00:02:12,803
Blue ice?
What is that then, blue ice?

15
00:02:12,846 --> 00:02:16,111
He was sitting in his car
outside a warehouse

16
00:02:16,149 --> 00:02:18,117
at Heathrow Airport

17
00:02:18,151 --> 00:02:22,611
when this great big chunk of ice,
the size of a refrigerator,

18
00:02:22,656 --> 00:02:25,318
broke off a jumbo-jet
toilet compartment

19
00:02:25,358 --> 00:02:28,327
and crashed straight through
the roof of his Jaguar.

20
00:02:28,361 --> 00:02:30,295
Stone dead.

21
00:02:30,330 --> 00:02:32,161
Oh.

22
00:02:32,199 --> 00:02:34,167
You're joking!

23
00:02:34,201 --> 00:02:36,328
Would l be joking
stood out here,

24
00:02:36,369 --> 00:02:38,837
£20 out for a wreath?

25
00:02:38,872 --> 00:02:42,569
43? That's tragic.

26
00:02:42,609 --> 00:02:45,510
Not really.
He was a violent bastard.

27
00:02:45,545 --> 00:02:47,513
The only reason
he was at the airport,

28
00:02:47,547 --> 00:02:49,538
he was planning
a cargo heist.

29
00:02:49,583 --> 00:02:52,450
...the Son
and the Holy Ghost, amen.

30
00:02:55,455 --> 00:02:57,252
- Hello, Charlie.
- Hello, Harry.

31
00:02:57,290 --> 00:02:58,757
You all right, luv?

32
00:02:58,792 --> 00:03:00,760
Thank you for making it.

33
00:03:00,794 --> 00:03:03,160
- Sorry about this.
- All right, mate.

34
00:03:12,239 --> 00:03:14,901
Say, you was having me on,
wasn't ya?

35
00:03:14,941 --> 00:03:16,704
No.

36
00:03:19,746 --> 00:03:22,715
''Waltham Stoneman
dies in freak accident.''

37
00:03:22,749 --> 00:03:26,879
'''Blue ice nothing
to panic about,'

38
00:03:26,920 --> 00:03:31,380
says airline spokesperson.''

39
00:03:31,424 --> 00:03:34,985
- Oh, dear.
- You never know, do you?

40
00:03:35,028 --> 00:03:36,996
Out of a clear sky,

41
00:03:37,030 --> 00:03:39,464
bang.

42
00:03:39,499 --> 00:03:41,467
lt doesn't bear
thinking about.

43
00:03:56,750 --> 00:03:58,615
- Hello?
- Hey, it's me, Kyle.

44
00:03:58,652 --> 00:04:01,086
- l told you not to call.
- Listen, don't hang up!

45
00:04:01,121 --> 00:04:02,645
lt's-- it's important, okay?

46
00:04:54,507 --> 00:04:55,667
l don't need to see you.

47
00:04:55,709 --> 00:04:58,234
l just want you to take
something down for me, okay?

48
00:04:58,278 --> 00:05:00,838
Just hurry up, okay?
l haven't got much time.

49
00:05:00,880 --> 00:05:05,180
X-P-L-A...

50
00:05:05,218 --> 00:05:07,618
- Kyle--
- Yeah, just take it down.

51
00:05:07,654 --> 00:05:10,088
C-l-F...

52
00:05:10,123 --> 00:05:14,958
Refer number: CVH-7 43.

53
00:05:29,609 --> 00:05:31,873
l do not believe this!

54
00:05:43,289 --> 00:05:45,484
Look what you've done
to my bloody car!

55
00:05:46,760 --> 00:05:48,250
What do you want me to do?

56
00:05:48,294 --> 00:05:51,195
l might have known, a woman driver
talking on her bloody car phone.

57
00:05:53,033 --> 00:05:55,729
Kyle...

58
00:05:55,769 --> 00:05:58,465
Kyle?

59
00:05:58,505 --> 00:06:00,473
Jeez.

60
00:06:00,507 --> 00:06:02,475
Hello?

61
00:06:02,509 --> 00:06:04,739
Kyle, are you there?

62
00:06:06,613 --> 00:06:07,875
Kyle?

63
00:06:13,953 --> 00:06:15,614
Finished our call now,
have we?

64
00:06:15,655 --> 00:06:17,316
Can l help you?

65
00:06:17,357 --> 00:06:19,723
Help me?
You've just destroyed my bloody car!

66
00:06:19,759 --> 00:06:22,455
You see that?
That is a traffic light.

67
00:06:22,495 --> 00:06:25,862
And when it turns red,
that means that the car in front of you

68
00:06:25,899 --> 00:06:27,867
is going to stop!

69
00:06:27,901 --> 00:06:29,869
- Are you hurt?
- Hurt? Oh!

70
00:06:29,903 --> 00:06:32,463
Apart from whiplash
and a few broken ribs, l'm fine.

71
00:06:32,505 --> 00:06:35,201
lt seems to me
the dent in my fender

72
00:06:35,241 --> 00:06:38,233
cancels out your rear
broken lamp, so we're even.

73
00:06:38,278 --> 00:06:40,576
- Even?!
- Bye.

74
00:06:47,821 --> 00:06:49,516
Right!

75
00:07:28,695 --> 00:07:30,663
What the hell do you
think you're doing?

76
00:07:30,697 --> 00:07:32,665
Oh, hello!

77
00:07:32,699 --> 00:07:34,667
lt's you again.

78
00:07:34,701 --> 00:07:37,295
Let's say we look
at the damage you claim l did.

79
00:07:40,073 --> 00:07:41,665
Fine.

80
00:07:43,076 --> 00:07:45,044
See?

81
00:07:45,078 --> 00:07:47,046
lt's just a nick!

82
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:49,640
The bumper's been buckled,
the brakelight's smashed,

83
00:07:49,682 --> 00:07:51,479
the exhaust is split.

84
00:07:51,518 --> 00:07:53,986
- lt will still go, won't it?
- Go? Of course it will go.

85
00:07:54,020 --> 00:07:57,319
Well, l know you are
going to tell me-- Mister...?

86
00:07:57,357 --> 00:07:58,984
Anders.
Harry Anders.

87
00:07:59,025 --> 00:08:01,960
Well, Mr. Anders,
are you going to let me buy you off?

88
00:08:01,995 --> 00:08:04,463
- The correct course of action--
- Oh, dear!

89
00:08:04,497 --> 00:08:07,091
The bore-me-
with-procedure type.

90
00:08:07,133 --> 00:08:11,331
l can't do it that way. The person who
owns that car would be very upset.

91
00:08:11,371 --> 00:08:14,101
Oh, the person who owns
that car would be upset?

92
00:08:14,140 --> 00:08:16,904
The person who owns this car
is bloody furious!

93
00:08:16,943 --> 00:08:19,571
Mr. Anders,
my name is Stacy.

94
00:08:19,612 --> 00:08:21,705
Would you like
to buy me a drink?

95
00:08:23,116 --> 00:08:24,583
Why would l do that?

96
00:08:24,617 --> 00:08:26,812
lf this argument's
going to be a long one,

97
00:08:26,853 --> 00:08:28,878
l'd rather be somewhere
a little warmer.

98
00:08:28,922 --> 00:08:31,652
Yeah.

99
00:08:31,691 --> 00:08:34,023
lt's been a chilly
afternoon, hasn't it?

100
00:08:34,727 --> 00:08:38,219
lf you send me the bill,
l'll pay for all the damages.

101
00:08:38,264 --> 00:08:41,392
This guy you are involved with,
the one who owns the car,

102
00:08:41,434 --> 00:08:43,629
are you that
frightened of him?

103
00:08:43,670 --> 00:08:45,729
Nobody is frightened of Lewis.

104
00:08:45,772 --> 00:08:47,797
He's a sweetheart.
lt's just that

105
00:08:47,841 --> 00:08:50,036
it isn't exactly
my first accident.

106
00:08:50,076 --> 00:08:53,011
And what does
''sweetheart'' do?

107
00:08:53,046 --> 00:08:55,173
Goes to parties,
tells okay jokes,

108
00:08:55,215 --> 00:08:57,513
and does what any
good diplomat does.

109
00:08:57,550 --> 00:08:59,711
Diplomat? Oh.

110
00:08:59,752 --> 00:09:02,152
l have a little problem
with diplomats.

111
00:09:02,188 --> 00:09:05,817
Me and the Vienna Convention
have a few miles on the clock.

112
00:09:05,859 --> 00:09:08,259
You don't seem like
the Foreign Office type.

113
00:09:08,294 --> 00:09:11,058
l was...

114
00:09:11,097 --> 00:09:13,998
sort of foreign office.

115
00:09:14,033 --> 00:09:16,593
Refill?

116
00:09:19,339 --> 00:09:22,206
You must know the owner
of this place pretty well.

117
00:09:22,242 --> 00:09:24,676
You could say that.
He's a wonderful guy.

118
00:09:24,711 --> 00:09:27,680
You?

119
00:09:30,183 --> 00:09:32,811
l pay the bills,
and l get the headaches.

120
00:09:32,852 --> 00:09:34,820
lt's the music
you really love, right?

121
00:09:34,854 --> 00:09:37,322
A little blues,
or soul maybe?

122
00:09:37,357 --> 00:09:39,325
- Jazz.
- Perfect!

123
00:09:39,359 --> 00:09:40,656
Go on.

124
00:09:41,995 --> 00:09:43,963
You don't make much money,

125
00:09:43,997 --> 00:09:47,330
and the apartment upstairs
has a kitchen that's... too small,

126
00:09:47,367 --> 00:09:49,426
and a bedroom
that's too big.

127
00:09:49,469 --> 00:09:52,165
But after all the headaches
it's the one place

128
00:09:52,205 --> 00:09:54,435
you value more than
anything else in the world.

129
00:09:54,474 --> 00:09:57,705
l knew a girl like you once.

130
00:09:57,744 --> 00:09:59,712
And l felt the same way about her

131
00:09:59,746 --> 00:10:02,909
as l feel about you.

132
00:10:02,949 --> 00:10:05,884
l didn't know whether
to love her or hate her.

133
00:10:05,919 --> 00:10:07,978
So what did you do?

134
00:10:08,021 --> 00:10:09,852
A little of both.

135
00:10:12,191 --> 00:10:14,159
Evening, Harry.

136
00:10:14,193 --> 00:10:17,253
- A little early, aren't you?
- Hi, Buddy.

137
00:10:17,297 --> 00:10:19,765
That's Buddy,
the jazz piano player.

138
00:10:19,799 --> 00:10:22,666
This is his rehearsal time.

139
00:10:22,702 --> 00:10:25,637
He's a very bad
piano player.

140
00:10:25,672 --> 00:10:28,300
lf he had a work permit
they'd kick him out of the country

141
00:10:28,341 --> 00:10:30,309
but he doesn't,
so l'm stuck with him.

142
00:10:30,343 --> 00:10:34,712
# Some day, we'll be
close together #

143
00:10:34,747 --> 00:10:36,715
# Wait and see #

144
00:10:36,749 --> 00:10:41,152
# Oh, by the way #

145
00:10:41,187 --> 00:10:45,749
# This time
the dream's on me... #

146
00:10:45,792 --> 00:10:49,455
- l'd better go.
- lf you go, you'll miss great jazz.

147
00:10:49,495 --> 00:10:54,626
# And you look at me
adoringly... #

148
00:10:54,667 --> 00:10:57,295
Stay.

149
00:10:57,337 --> 00:10:59,703
# This time the dream's
on me. #

150
00:11:23,396 --> 00:11:25,489
Here you are, sir.

151
00:12:03,069 --> 00:12:05,867
You really do love it,
don't you?

152
00:12:05,905 --> 00:12:08,237
There are easier ways
of making a living.

153
00:12:08,274 --> 00:12:10,640
But jazz clubs are special.

154
00:12:10,676 --> 00:12:12,803
l've got High Court judges
sitting out there,

155
00:12:12,845 --> 00:12:16,008
alongside some of the worst
villains in London--

156
00:12:16,049 --> 00:12:18,916
lords, hookers.

157
00:12:18,951 --> 00:12:22,352
There's a guy over there
who drives a refuse truck.

158
00:12:22,388 --> 00:12:24,686
There's a Chinese man
with one leg.

159
00:12:24,724 --> 00:12:27,352
What do they all
have in common?

160
00:12:27,393 --> 00:12:30,726
Loving jazz, like l do.

161
00:12:32,498 --> 00:12:34,227
Tea leaf's been in again,
Mr. Anders.

162
00:12:34,267 --> 00:12:36,428
Cleaned out three handbags
and a gent's wallet.

163
00:12:36,469 --> 00:12:40,030
- Not now, George.
- All right, all right.

164
00:12:42,575 --> 00:12:45,169
- What's a tea leaf?
- Thief.

165
00:12:45,211 --> 00:12:46,678
Cockney rhyming slang.

166
00:12:46,712 --> 00:12:49,579
Trouble and strife, wife.
Apples and pears, stairs.

167
00:12:49,615 --> 00:12:52,379
So what are you going to do
with this tea leaf when you find him?

168
00:12:52,418 --> 00:12:55,819
- Break his dairy farm.
- Arm.

169
00:12:58,124 --> 00:13:00,922
Excuse me.
A bit of a squabble.

170
00:13:07,834 --> 00:13:09,324
All right, lads, that'll do.

171
00:13:12,972 --> 00:13:15,065
All right, leave the furniture
out of this.

172
00:13:16,642 --> 00:13:20,169
How many times have l got to ban you
before you start taking me--

173
00:13:28,921 --> 00:13:30,650
Shit!

174
00:13:30,690 --> 00:13:34,558
You went for the stomach,
Harry. That's risky.

175
00:13:34,594 --> 00:13:37,062
Hit a man in the chin
and he'll go down.

176
00:13:37,096 --> 00:13:39,064
That's what my dad
used to say.

177
00:13:39,098 --> 00:13:41,965
Your dad was right, but Ronnie
is a steady customer,

178
00:13:42,001 --> 00:13:44,731
and you never hit
a steady customer in the face.

179
00:13:44,770 --> 00:13:47,432
They don't come back
till their bruises are gone.

180
00:13:53,813 --> 00:13:56,247
Do you like
all music, Harry?

181
00:13:56,282 --> 00:13:58,944
- Some of it.
- Classical music?

182
00:13:58,985 --> 00:14:01,351
Everything
except Schoenberg.

183
00:14:01,387 --> 00:14:04,288
Schoenberg always struck me
as being a bit of a wanker.

184
00:14:19,071 --> 00:14:21,096
l'll be in touch.

185
00:14:23,509 --> 00:14:25,443
Bye.

186
00:14:46,332 --> 00:14:49,165
Hm, looks a bit fancy, Harry.

187
00:14:49,202 --> 00:14:51,170
Opera, the Covent Garden.

188
00:14:51,204 --> 00:14:54,935
Opera? Not exactly
your speed, Harry. Who's it from?

189
00:14:54,974 --> 00:14:57,204
You're beginning to sound
like my mum, George.

190
00:14:57,243 --> 00:14:59,302
Don't be ridiculous.

191
00:15:00,746 --> 00:15:02,577
Don't be too late
coming home, dear.

192
00:15:21,400 --> 00:15:23,129
You're late.

193
00:15:26,005 --> 00:15:29,873
But on account of that dress,
l'm prepared to forgive you.

194
00:15:29,909 --> 00:15:31,706
Shh-hh.

195
00:15:46,092 --> 00:15:48,583
Don't you just
love the opera, Harry?

196
00:15:48,628 --> 00:15:52,155
You could say
l enjoyed it for the spectacle.

197
00:15:52,198 --> 00:15:55,361
So where are we
going to eat?

198
00:15:55,401 --> 00:15:57,995
l think l know just the place.

199
00:15:58,037 --> 00:16:00,005
Wonderful ambiance,

200
00:16:00,039 --> 00:16:01,666
great food...

201
00:16:01,707 --> 00:16:03,470
Will it still be open?

202
00:16:03,509 --> 00:16:05,443
24 hours a day.

203
00:16:08,114 --> 00:16:10,082
How much longer?

204
00:16:10,116 --> 00:16:13,279
l'd say about 14...

205
00:16:13,319 --> 00:16:15,583
minutes.

206
00:16:19,358 --> 00:16:22,623
l don't know how anyone
has the patience for cooking.

207
00:16:22,662 --> 00:16:24,596
l can't handle
all that waiting.

208
00:16:24,630 --> 00:16:28,031
Waiting, Stacy, is the key.

209
00:16:28,067 --> 00:16:30,126
l remember my old man
used to say,

210
00:16:30,169 --> 00:16:33,002
''Harry,'' he'd say,

211
00:16:33,039 --> 00:16:36,634
''waiting is what cooking
is all about.

212
00:16:36,676 --> 00:16:39,304
The longer you wait,

213
00:16:39,345 --> 00:16:42,075
the better it tastes.''

214
00:16:44,083 --> 00:16:49,020
l have a feeling
you're a wonderful cook, Harry.

215
00:16:49,055 --> 00:16:51,649
l never met a man
who enjoyed waiting before.

216
00:17:07,907 --> 00:17:11,172
Of course, a lot of what
my old man told me was crap.

217
00:17:53,686 --> 00:17:56,712
You know what you are, Stacy?

218
00:17:56,756 --> 00:17:59,589
You're blue ice.

219
00:17:59,625 --> 00:18:01,820
Blue ice?
What's blue ice?

220
00:18:01,861 --> 00:18:04,830
lt's when--

221
00:18:04,864 --> 00:18:07,697
it's when
something unexpected

222
00:18:07,733 --> 00:18:11,169
and wonderful falls on you
out of a clear blue sky...

223
00:18:11,203 --> 00:18:13,535
and changes your life.

224
00:18:13,572 --> 00:18:15,699
What a great image.

225
00:18:16,709 --> 00:18:18,506
You know something?

226
00:18:18,544 --> 00:18:21,308
You are a very interesting
person, Harry.

227
00:18:21,347 --> 00:18:24,316
- lnteresting?
- Yeah.

228
00:18:24,350 --> 00:18:26,079
Very.

229
00:18:28,154 --> 00:18:29,781
Parachute Regiment?

230
00:18:29,822 --> 00:18:32,518
Military lntelligence?

231
00:18:32,558 --> 00:18:36,085
Northern lreland,
Middle East, Eastern Europe.

232
00:18:36,128 --> 00:18:39,586
And in 1982...

233
00:18:39,632 --> 00:18:41,623
compulsory retirement.

234
00:18:41,667 --> 00:18:45,034
Should l be flattered?

235
00:18:45,070 --> 00:18:47,937
Or do you do this much
research on everyone?

236
00:18:47,973 --> 00:18:51,704
l have to be careful who l get
involved with, don't l?

237
00:18:55,347 --> 00:18:59,215
You were a spy,
weren't you, Harry?

238
00:18:59,251 --> 00:19:00,878
l adore you, Stacy.

239
00:19:00,920 --> 00:19:02,888
And if l lie here long enough,

240
00:19:02,922 --> 00:19:06,085
l'd probably tell you everything
about my life anyway.

241
00:19:06,125 --> 00:19:09,720
But l don't like you digging
in the nooks and crannies of my past.

242
00:19:12,164 --> 00:19:13,654
Why did they fire you?

243
00:19:13,699 --> 00:19:16,259
The Czech agent
broke the rules,

244
00:19:16,302 --> 00:19:18,793
he hurt the wife
of one of my sources.

245
00:19:18,838 --> 00:19:21,329
They asked me to ignore it.
l couldn't.

246
00:19:23,309 --> 00:19:24,867
So what happened?

247
00:19:24,910 --> 00:19:27,811
l took him up onto the roof
of my office building.

248
00:19:29,181 --> 00:19:32,412
- And?
- The Czech bounced.

249
00:20:03,682 --> 00:20:06,617
l get a refill, please?

250
00:20:15,961 --> 00:20:18,122
Hi.

251
00:20:21,600 --> 00:20:25,036
Give me an hour, Harry,
and then we can sneak away.

252
00:20:25,070 --> 00:20:28,198
l have to introduce some people
to the American Ambassador.

253
00:20:28,240 --> 00:20:30,208
Of course you do.
l'll tell you what,

254
00:20:30,242 --> 00:20:32,210
why don't l say hello?

255
00:20:32,244 --> 00:20:34,644
lt's been a long time
since l've met an ambassador.

256
00:20:34,680 --> 00:20:36,648
- You want to?
- Sure.

257
00:20:36,682 --> 00:20:38,343
Okay.

258
00:20:40,986 --> 00:20:43,819
- Thank you very much.
