00:40:43,988 --> 00:40:46,923
- Either he knew the killer--
- Or he thought he could trust him.

508
00:40:46,958 --> 00:40:49,825
- Or her.
- You think the woman's involved?

509
00:40:49,861 --> 00:40:53,524
l don't know yet. l phoned her
that night, but she didn't show up.

510
00:40:53,564 --> 00:40:56,089
Obviously got mixed up
in something very dodgy.

511
00:40:56,134 --> 00:40:58,432
Or somebody
you'd recognize again.

512
00:41:01,205 --> 00:41:03,332
lt doesn't look very good
for the lady, Harry.

513
00:41:03,374 --> 00:41:05,706
lt doesn't, does it?

514
00:41:05,743 --> 00:41:07,711
The police were told to lay off?

515
00:41:07,745 --> 00:41:09,736
They faked the inquest.

516
00:41:09,781 --> 00:41:12,477
The body bag sent direct
to the United States,

517
00:41:12,517 --> 00:41:15,145
courtesy of the U.S. Army.
lt's gotta be a spook, Harry.

518
00:41:15,186 --> 00:41:17,620
Nobody else could pull
strings like that.

519
00:41:17,655 --> 00:41:19,953
Do you know anyone
in the American Embassy?

520
00:41:19,991 --> 00:41:21,788
Are you kidding?

521
00:41:21,826 --> 00:41:24,693
l've got contacts
in the Secret Service, the ClA,

522
00:41:24,729 --> 00:41:27,698
the N.S.A., the D.E.A., the l.R.S.,
Tobacco and Firearms,

523
00:41:27,732 --> 00:41:30,929
and a few organizations
l don't even know the initials of.

524
00:41:30,968 --> 00:41:33,198
Find out who it was,
and l'll take it from there.

525
00:41:33,237 --> 00:41:35,705
- What, just like that?
- Yeah.

526
00:41:35,740 --> 00:41:37,367
Harry Anders,

527
00:41:37,408 --> 00:41:39,774
10 years retired and still
looking for trouble?

528
00:41:39,811 --> 00:41:42,837
You think l'm rusty?

529
00:41:42,880 --> 00:41:45,440
lt's been a long time, pal.
Here.

530
00:41:53,791 --> 00:41:55,816
Let's see if l remember.

531
00:42:51,215 --> 00:42:52,477
Dropped a stitch.

532
00:42:57,488 --> 00:42:59,615
lf the nightclub
don't work out, Harry,

533
00:42:59,657 --> 00:43:01,750
maybe you come see me, huh?

534
00:43:11,435 --> 00:43:13,460
Great.

535
00:43:17,708 --> 00:43:20,939
- What do you think of them?
- Looking good, Harry.

536
00:43:20,978 --> 00:43:23,606
- Great.
- Good, huh? Don't you think?

537
00:43:25,616 --> 00:43:28,050
- Hi, Joe.
- Hello, Harry.

538
00:43:36,694 --> 00:43:38,662
Excuse me.

539
00:43:38,696 --> 00:43:40,994
Um, the name is Stevens.

540
00:43:42,066 --> 00:43:44,660
Um, you're Harry Anders,
aren't you?

541
00:43:44,702 --> 00:43:47,227
Yeah. Have you been
here before?

542
00:43:47,271 --> 00:43:50,206
Oh, yeah. Not as often
as l'd have liked.

543
00:43:50,241 --> 00:43:52,675
- Join me in a whiskey?
- Sure.

544
00:43:59,450 --> 00:44:02,283
- Do you like them?
- Yep.

545
00:44:02,320 --> 00:44:05,118
The horn player's a bit rusty.
He keeps missing the bridge.

546
00:44:06,223 --> 00:44:08,191
He'll warm up.

547
00:44:08,225 --> 00:44:10,557
He always starts a bit tame.

548
00:44:13,030 --> 00:44:15,590
You seem to know
your music, Mr. Stevens.

549
00:44:15,633 --> 00:44:17,931
l've got a set of...

550
00:44:17,969 --> 00:44:20,335
Kid Ory's 1921 recordings
on the Sunshine label.

551
00:44:20,371 --> 00:44:23,636
As far as l know it's the only full set
in the whole of England.

552
00:44:23,674 --> 00:44:25,938
The San Francisco sessions?

553
00:44:25,977 --> 00:44:29,572
Yeah! Yeah, including
''Society Blues,'' yeah.

554
00:44:29,613 --> 00:44:32,411
l am impressed.

555
00:44:37,021 --> 00:44:40,013
Like a code, isn't it? Music.

556
00:44:40,057 --> 00:44:42,025
Especially jazz.

557
00:44:42,059 --> 00:44:44,357
You take the notes of the tune
and you change them

558
00:44:44,395 --> 00:44:46,363
according to
the rules of jazz.

559
00:44:46,397 --> 00:44:48,365
Stride piano, say.

560
00:44:48,399 --> 00:44:50,367
And you hope
that the message,

561
00:44:50,401 --> 00:44:53,427
the... melody still
comes through.

562
00:44:53,471 --> 00:44:56,133
lt comes through if you
know how to decode it.

563
00:44:56,173 --> 00:44:59,370
For which you have to know
how to listen, what to look out for.

564
00:45:06,751 --> 00:45:09,151
Which is what happens
in life sometimes, isn't it?

565
00:45:09,186 --> 00:45:12,747
Something happens-- puzzling
because you don't have the key.

566
00:45:12,790 --> 00:45:15,816
You don't know the rules
of what jazz it is that they're playing,

567
00:45:15,860 --> 00:45:17,987
so the music doesn't
seem to make sense.

568
00:45:18,029 --> 00:45:20,224
You can't figure out
what's going on.

569
00:45:21,966 --> 00:45:24,526
lt's just noise.

570
00:45:24,568 --> 00:45:26,399
Who sent you?

571
00:45:31,342 --> 00:45:35,108
To find that out, Mr. Anders, you just
have to follow the music, won't you?

572
00:46:00,438 --> 00:46:02,497
l'm sorry, sir.
He's busy at the moment.

573
00:46:02,540 --> 00:46:05,907
l don't care how busy he is, pal!

574
00:46:05,943 --> 00:46:08,639
Get him! lt's a priority.

575
00:46:08,679 --> 00:46:12,979
No no, he's gone now, sir.
Disappeared. Don't know where he is.

576
00:46:51,822 --> 00:46:54,484
15 Mapleton Drive.

577
00:46:54,525 --> 00:46:56,493
You've been here before?

578
00:46:56,527 --> 00:46:58,495
Yep.

579
00:46:58,529 --> 00:47:01,862
l once babysat a Russian defector
here for three months.

580
00:47:01,899 --> 00:47:04,527
About 20 years ago.

581
00:47:04,568 --> 00:47:07,366
He had very bad breath
and played with himself a lot.

582
00:47:22,019 --> 00:47:23,987
l'll just go get us a drink.

583
00:47:24,021 --> 00:47:26,080
Fine.

584
00:47:36,300 --> 00:47:38,268
Hot chocolate.

585
00:47:38,302 --> 00:47:41,533
lt's very warming
this time of night.

586
00:47:41,572 --> 00:47:43,767
l never go to bed
without one.

587
00:47:49,180 --> 00:47:51,375
So, what's going on?

588
00:47:55,553 --> 00:47:59,148
l'm not a field operative as
you've probably already realized.

589
00:48:00,691 --> 00:48:03,091
l understand you were,
and a very good one too.

590
00:48:05,529 --> 00:48:08,191
Until you overstepped
the bounds...

591
00:48:08,232 --> 00:48:10,928
got a bit too physical
on an assignment.

592
00:48:13,170 --> 00:48:15,900
This isn't ''This ls Your Life,
Harry Anders.''

593
00:48:15,940 --> 00:48:17,237
No.

594
00:48:17,274 --> 00:48:20,505
So how come l'm suddenly
up to my ass

595
00:48:20,544 --> 00:48:23,638
in British and American security
and intelligence guys?

596
00:48:26,150 --> 00:48:28,675
Think of all that's been
happening as music, as jazz.

597
00:48:31,689 --> 00:48:34,487
lt sounds jumbled.

598
00:48:34,525 --> 00:48:37,323
Somebody upstairs is playing
a different tune entirely.

599
00:48:40,431 --> 00:48:43,525
But if you listen hard enough,
somewhere...

600
00:48:43,567 --> 00:48:45,865
somewhere in the middle...

601
00:48:47,538 --> 00:48:49,563
you can hear the melody.

602
00:49:00,818 --> 00:49:02,786
Where is everybody?

603
00:49:02,820 --> 00:49:04,788
No problem, Harry.

604
00:49:04,822 --> 00:49:06,790
Tell them
what they wanna know.

605
00:49:06,824 --> 00:49:08,792
Problem?

606
00:49:08,826 --> 00:49:10,794
Who's got a problem?

607
00:49:10,828 --> 00:49:13,456
Let me give you
a piece of advice, Harry.

608
00:49:16,133 --> 00:49:18,601
Let go of me, you fucks!

609
00:49:20,804 --> 00:49:23,830
# Someday somewhere... #

610
00:49:23,874 --> 00:49:26,638
# We'll be close together,
wait and see... #

611
00:49:26,677 --> 00:49:29,111
You know your music,
don't you, Harry?

612
00:49:29,146 --> 00:49:31,080
Don't let them hurt me!

613
00:49:31,115 --> 00:49:33,083
# By the way #

614
00:49:33,117 --> 00:49:36,245
# This time
the dream's on me. #

615
00:49:52,169 --> 00:49:54,137
l think we're gonna
have trouble here.

616
00:49:54,171 --> 00:49:57,368
Stop harassing me.
l didn't know he was an agent.

617
00:49:57,408 --> 00:49:59,205
l just told him,
l don't know anything.

618
00:49:59,243 --> 00:50:01,438
We're not gonna get
very far like this, are we?

619
00:50:01,478 --> 00:50:03,969
- You're lying.
- Why would l be lying?

620
00:50:05,349 --> 00:50:08,045
Why are you doing this?
lt's all a mistake!

621
00:50:08,085 --> 00:50:10,713
You'll just have
to follow the music.

622
00:50:10,754 --> 00:50:12,221
Tell them what
you did in there.

623
00:50:12,256 --> 00:50:14,554
- l run a jazz club.
- My name is Harry Anders.

624
00:50:14,591 --> 00:50:17,492
- Come on, Harry, tell them.
- My name is Harry Anders!

625
00:50:17,528 --> 00:50:20,554
- Don't know what you're talking about.
- lt's so easy.

626
00:50:20,597 --> 00:50:22,531
l do not know anything!

627
00:50:22,566 --> 00:50:27,503
- Respectful of the bloody training.
- l do not know anything!

628
00:50:27,538 --> 00:50:29,403
l do not know anything!

629
00:50:29,440 --> 00:50:32,068
- You know the rules, Harry.
- l can't tell you anything.

630
00:50:32,109 --> 00:50:34,077
Tell us what we want to know.

631
00:50:34,111 --> 00:50:36,579
Tell us what we want to know
if you care about the girl.

632
00:50:40,684 --> 00:50:42,618
Tell them what they
wanna know, Harry.

633
00:50:42,653 --> 00:50:45,383
- The horn player's a bit rusty.
- Stop, l can't see.

634
00:50:45,422 --> 00:50:48,687
You're a bit rusty, Harry.
You have to know how to listen.

635
00:50:48,726 --> 00:50:51,593
Here we meet again.
Just fucking keep on doing it!

636
00:50:51,628 --> 00:50:54,620
l can do it all bloody night
if l want! Now tell me!

637
00:50:57,534 --> 00:50:59,798
l don't know anything!

638
00:51:00,804 --> 00:51:02,465
Harry?

639
00:51:07,745 --> 00:51:09,212
You're a bit rusty, Harry.

640
00:51:09,246 --> 00:51:11,908
You're a bit rusty.
You're a bit rusty, Harry.

641
00:51:14,818 --> 00:51:19,619
Fuck you!
C-V-H-7-4-3

642
00:51:19,656 --> 00:51:22,284
You should have
told them, Harry.

643
00:51:25,229 --> 00:51:28,198
Fuck you!
l don't know anything.

644
00:53:14,872 --> 00:53:16,863
Bastards.

645
00:53:35,592 --> 00:53:37,253
Hop in, sir.

646
00:53:55,145 --> 00:53:57,375
Driving is not too bad there
this time of day.

647
00:53:57,414 --> 00:53:59,439
We should make it
in 50 minutes nicely.

648
00:54:08,425 --> 00:54:11,622
Do you mind if l--?

649
00:54:11,662 --> 00:54:14,358
l do find it relaxing.

650
00:54:14,398 --> 00:54:15,922
Helps the day go by.

651
00:54:27,210 --> 00:54:30,270
We're authorized
to the lounge.

652
00:54:33,317 --> 00:54:35,444
Carry on, sir.

653
00:54:46,597 --> 00:54:49,088
We're here, Mr. Anders, sir.

654
00:54:53,971 --> 00:54:57,532
The revised E.T.A. of the Minister's plane
is 11-0-0 hours.

655
00:54:57,574 --> 00:54:59,974
l've made arrangements
to put the press conference

656
00:55:00,010 --> 00:55:02,808
and the reception at the Foreign Office
back by three hours.

657
00:55:02,846 --> 00:55:04,814
No.

658
00:55:04,848 --> 00:55:06,816
A little breakfast,
Sir Hector?

659
00:55:14,191 --> 00:55:16,659
Better make that breakfast
for two, l think.

660
00:55:16,693 --> 00:55:20,151
What have you been up to, Harry?
You look absolutely ghastly.

661
00:55:20,197 --> 00:55:22,165
l wish l could say
the same about you, Sir.

662
00:55:22,199 --> 00:55:24,030
Being a lord suits you.

663
00:55:24,067 --> 00:55:26,968
Oh, no no, just a humble baronet,
dear boy.

664
00:55:27,004 --> 00:55:29,165
l never thought of you
as the humble type, Sir.

665
00:55:29,206 --> 00:55:33,074
They felt l had to have something when
they put me out to grass.

666
00:55:33,110 --> 00:55:35,578
Knighthood was probably
the cheapest.

667
00:55:35,612 --> 00:55:38,581
Gave me compulsory
early retirement, you know,

668
00:55:38,615 --> 00:55:40,583
into the protocol division.

669
00:55:40,617 --> 00:55:44,451
l'm just a greaser now,
a handshake in a business suit.

670
00:55:44,488 --> 00:55:46,456
Yes.

671
00:55:46,490 --> 00:55:48,458
l've always admired
your handshake, Sir.

672
00:55:48,492 --> 00:55:50,551
Very firm.

673
00:55:52,829 --> 00:55:55,525
Are you waiting
for somebody now?

674
00:55:55,565 --> 00:55:57,533
Yes, the Finance Minister
of Nepal.

675
00:55:57,567 --> 00:56:00,331
You're joking.

676
00:56:00,370 --> 00:56:01,928
No, l'm not.

677
00:56:01,972 --> 00:56:04,907
Why don't you have some
double kidneys? They're delicious.

678
00:56:04,941 --> 00:56:06,203
No, thank you.

679
00:56:08,111 --> 00:56:10,102
Do you still have that club?

680
00:56:10,147 --> 00:56:11,671
Just about.

681
00:56:11,715 --> 00:56:13,876
l'll have to pop in there
one day.

682
00:56:13,917 --> 00:56:16,408
Do that. Bring the Finance Minister
with you.

683
00:56:16,453 --> 00:56:18,421
Tuesday nights
is Nepalese night.

684
00:56:18,455 --> 00:56:19,717
Very popular.

685
00:56:25,862 --> 00:56:28,262
Are you gonna tell me what
the hell is going on, Sir?

686
00:56:28,298 --> 00:56:30,596
Or do l just
stand here guessing?

687
00:56:32,469 --> 00:56:35,768
l had forgotten how insolent
you actually are, Anders.

688
00:56:39,576 --> 00:56:42,238
The Americans are up to something.
They won't cut us in.

689
00:56:42,279 --> 00:56:44,076
lt is thought
you might know.

690
00:56:44,114 --> 00:56:46,241
l couldn't have been
asked nicely?

691
00:56:46,283 --> 00:56:48,945
Did it have to be
done like that?

692
00:56:48,985 --> 00:56:50,748
Now, l wasn't party
to that decision.

693
00:56:50,787 --> 00:56:52,755
l'm just a handshake
now, remember?

694
00:56:52,789 --> 00:56:55,280
Have some toast.

695
00:56:55,325 --> 00:56:57,691
You recruited me,
and you ran me.

696
00:56:57,728 --> 00:56:59,696
lf you're so far
out of the loop,

697
00:56:59,730 --> 00:57:01,698
how come l'm here
talking to you?

698
00:57:01,732 --> 00:57:03,962
That was rather
unnecessary, Anders.

699
00:57:07,037 --> 00:57:09,005
Look, you're here
unofficially,

700
00:57:09,039 --> 00:57:11,269
l'm warning you unofficially.

701
00:57:12,476 --> 00:57:14,410
Just stay out of this.

702
00:57:14,444 --> 00:57:17,311
- Stay out of what?
- This is all above my head.

703
00:57:17,347 --> 00:57:19,315
All l know is that
you're a target.

704
00:57:19,349 --> 00:57:22,682
l don't want you to be any more
of one than you already are.

705
00:57:22,719 --> 00:57:26,382
l don't have to do what you say.
l don't work for you anymore.

706
00:57:26,423 --> 00:57:28,482
l don't think you have
any choice, dear boy.

707
00:57:28,525 --> 00:57:30,493
That's where you're wrong,
Sir Hector,

708
00:57:30,527 --> 00:57:32,392
because l have all kinds
of choices.

709
00:57:32,429 --> 00:57:35,660
l can go straight out of here around
to Grovener Square for example,

710
00:57:35,699 --> 00:57:38,896
and kick up such a fuss that l get in
to see the American Ambassador--

711
00:57:38,935 --> 00:57:41,403
with whom, as it happens,
l am on first-name terms.

712
00:57:41,438 --> 00:57:44,271
And l could tell him that something stinks
in his embassy,

713
00:57:44,307 --> 00:57:45,968
and that he ought
to know about it.

714
00:57:46,009 --> 00:57:48,705
That would mean the embassy's security
staff got involved.

715
00:57:48,745 --> 00:57:50,872
- We don't want that.
- Well...

716
00:57:50,914 --> 00:57:53,212
as a matter of fact, Sir Hector,

717
00:57:53,250 --> 00:57:55,912
l get on pretty well
with Americans.

718
00:57:55,952 --> 00:57:58,250
They're looking
for you, Harry.

719
00:57:59,956 --> 00:58:02,254
They want to talk to you
about Sam Garcia.

720
00:58:14,604 --> 00:58:17,732
Before he was shot,
he was worked over with a knife

721
00:58:17,774 --> 00:58:20,265
to see what he knew.

722
00:58:20,310 --> 00:58:22,642
The Americans are very angry
with you, Harry.

723
00:58:24,881 --> 00:58:27,145
You see, Garcia had
a lot of friends here.

724
00:58:46,970 --> 00:58:48,938
My name is Stacy.

725
00:58:48,972 --> 00:58:51,304
Would you like
to buy me a drink?

726
00:58:51,341 --> 00:58:53,901
Harry, l'm so happy.

727
00:58:53,944 --> 00:58:56,469
You don't fool me.
l know men like you, remember?

728
00:58:56,513 --> 00:58:58,879
- Come to bed, Harry.
- All that tough-guy talk...

729
00:58:58,915 --> 00:59:01,611
- Harry, come to bed.
- ...scar tissue on the outside,

730
00:59:01,651 --> 00:59:03,983
hopeless romantics
on the inside.

731
00:59:45,829 --> 00:59:49,060
l think you'd better tell me
what the hell is going on.

732
00:59:49,099 --> 00:59:51,329
- Nothing is going on.
- What are you doing here!?

733
00:59:51,368 --> 00:59:54,394
l'm not here. l never was.

734
00:59:54,437 --> 00:59:56,428
l just came to get my things.

735
00:59:57,874 --> 01:00:01,071
- Who was Kyle?
- You just don't understand.

736
01:00:01,111 --> 01:00:04,171
l understand that you used me
to get two of my friends killed

737
01:00:04,214 --> 01:00:06,375
and every spook
in London on my tail.

738
01:00:06,416 --> 01:00:07,474
You're hurting me.

739
01:00:07,517 --> 01:00:09,849
l'll hurt you even more
if l don't get some answers.

740
01:00:09,886 --> 01:00:11,444
Now who was Kyle?

741
01:00:11,488 --> 01:00:14,150
He was my ex-boyfriend,
like l told you.

742
01:00:14,190 --> 01:00:16,681
What l didn't tell you was...

743
01:00:16,726 --> 01:00:19,820
he worked for Military
lntelligence.

744
01:00:19,863 --> 01:00:21,888
Christ.

745
01:00:28,705 --> 01:00:31,196
Then why didn't you even
show up at the hotel?

746
01:00:32,676 --> 01:00:35,770
l did come to the hotel,
but it was crawling with police.

747
01:00:35,812 --> 01:00:37,780
l knew something
must have happened.

748
01:00:37,814 --> 01:00:39,782
You're damn right
something happened.

749
01:00:39,816 --> 01:00:42,944
l couldn't get involved.
lt would destroy Lewis.

750
01:00:42,986 --> 01:00:45,045
Fuck Lewis. You left me
